<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
Dr. Peters: Hello Mrs. Parker, how have you been?
Mrs. Parker: Hello Dr. Peters. Just fine thank you. Ricky and I are here for his vaccines.
Dr. Peters: Very well. Let's see, according to his vaccination record, Ricky has received his Polio, Tetanus and Hepatitis B shots. He is 14 months old, so he is due for Hepatitis A, Chickenpox and Measles shots.
Mrs. Parker: What about Rubella and Mumps?
Dr. Peters: Well, I can only give him these for now, and after a couple of weeks I can administer the rest.
Mrs. Parker: OK, great. Doctor, I think I also may need a Tetanus booster. Last time I got it was maybe fifteen years ago!
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
John: I have never done this before and don't know where to begin as far as making an offer on this house.
Agent: Hi, just be relaxed. Leave the details of making the offer up to me. Now, please tell me. What were you thinking you should offer?
John: All I know is that I absolutely must have this house! And I think I shall pay three hundred and fifty thousand dollars or more.
Agent: It is best to start a little low on the first bid to allow for a counter-offer. How about offering three hundred and twenty thousand dollars?
John: I hope that the owners aren't insulted by that offer.
Agent: Your offering price is not out-of-line. The owners will either take it or make a counter-offer.
John: Does it usually take very long for the owners to get back to you with an acceptance?
Agent: It usually doesn't take very long for owners to respond to an offer.
John: Should I be in touch with my bank to tell them to get the loan papers ready?
Agent: The only thing you should do now is relax. You already are pre-qualified for your loan.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
Linda: Hello, Joan. Why are you late today? You are never late for work.
Joan: No, I never am, but...
Linda: Wow! Your coat's very dirty! Did you fall?
Joan: Yes, I had a terrible experience on the underground train. Listen to this! A man came up to me and pulled out a knife. He pointed it right at me!
Linda: Oh, no! Are you all right? Did he hurt you?
Joan: No, he didn't hurt me, but he took my handbag.
Linda: Then what happened? What did you do?
Joan: I caught hold of his knife, and he pushed me to the floor.
Linda: Oh, no! Why did you catch hold of his knife? That's dangerous.
Joan: I don't know. I didn't think.
Linda: And what did the other passengers do? Did they help you?
Joan: Yes, they did. Two men ran after the robber and held him.
Linda: Did the police come?
Joan: Yeah. The conductor called a policeman, and he took the robber to the police station.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
Jason: Hey, Robbie. You're completely wet and covered with powder. So many colors! I mean, you look like a rainbow. What happened?
Robbie: I've just come back from visiting my family. You know, we're from India and today is our Spring Festival Day. We call it Holly.
Jason: That's all very interesting. But I still don't understand why you look like that?
Robbie: Well, we celebrate Holly by throwing colored powder and colored water at each other. And we light big fires, too, to show thanks to the gods.
Jason: Interesting. But aren't you afraid that you'll catch a cold and get ill? I mean, you're completely wet.
Robbie: Actually, the things we throw at each other helped to keep us healthy.
Jason: What do you mean?
Robbie: Well, the colored powders we throw are made from traditional Indian medicines.
Jason: And the coloured water, too?
Robbie: The coloured water comes from the yellow flowers called Palash, and they're good for you, too.
Jason: Amazing. It sounds like a lot of fun.
Robbie: It really is. Next year, if you're interested, I'll bring you along.
Jason: That would be great. I'll make sure I keep February second free.
Robbie: Actually, Holly isn't like Christmas. The date changes from year to year. It's always celebrated at the end of the winter season, on the last full moon day of the month.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
Mrs. Smith: Come in, please.
Mr. Sun: Good morning, Mrs. Smith.
Mrs. Smith: Good morning. You are Mr. Sun, aren't you? Take a seat, please.
Mr. Sun: Yes, thank you.
Mrs. Smith: I've noticed from your resume that you majored in accounting at Peking University. Will you please tell me something about your related courses?
Mr. Sun: In the first academic year we learned Principles of Accounting, and in the following years we learned Cost Accounting, Commercial Accounting, Industrial Accounting, and Management Accounting.
Mrs. Smith: Have you taken Accounting for Decision-Making and Control?
Mr. Sun: No, we haven't taken such a course, but we have taken a more specialized course for decision making, by the name of Forecasting and Decision-Making.
Mrs. Smith: From your school report card, I can see you did well in every course. But our advertisement says we need an accountant with practical work experience.
Mr. Sun: I forgot to include my experience as an accountant in my resume. In fact, I took a part-time job as an accountant at the Atlantic Trading Company during my second and third school year. I worked three evenings a week there and I did quite well. Here is the recommendation.
Mrs. Smith: You can speak English fluently but I wonder if you can deal with bookkeeping and accounting in English.
Mr. Sun: No problem. The professional English course is just English for Accounting. Moreover, as you know, the Atlantic Trading Company is a Sino-Australian joint venture. When I served part-time there, I became well acquainted with accounting operated in English.
Mrs. Smith: That sounds fine. Why did you choose to apply to our company?
Mr. Sun: I have a relative working as a manager in your manufacturing department. Her name is Lilling. She told me a lot about your company and I became quite interested. I believe I can have a promising career with the development of this company.
Mrs. Smith: Do you know something about the payment we give to our employees?
Mr. Sun: No, can you tell me about it?
Mrs. Smith: Of course. As for an entry-level accountant, we pay 1,500 a month in the first half-year. We have a grading system to evaluate your work. If you have made progress, we will certainly raise your salary. For beginners with a CPA certificate, they can earn at least 2,000 a month.
Mr. Sun: I have passed the five courses required by the Chinese CPA Association, but the certificate won't come to hand until next month. How about that?
Mrs. Smith: I hope you can show me your CPA certificate before we reach a decision by the end of July.
Mr. Sun: Thank you, Mrs. Smith. It is really a pleasure talking with you.
Mrs. Smith: The same for me. We'll keep in touch with you.
Mr. Sun: Thank you. Good-bye.
<END CONVERSATION>

Sarah: Really? That's good news for me.

Sarah: It sounds great!
Mr. Charles: You can also get a bonus at the end of the year, and if you can keep working in the company, your salary will get a raise every year.
Sarah: By the way, how many days do we work every week?
Mr. Charles: Five days every week, but if it is necessary, you need to work overtime once in a while.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
Tom: What are we going to do? I can't get the car out of this ditch. I'm stuck!
Jenny: I'm worried, Tom. I haven't seen any other cars for almost an hour.
Tom: I know. This is terrible. What can we do? This snow doesn't stop falling!
Jenny: I told you we should have stayed in town today. The weather report said 100 percent chance of snow. Why did you want to come up here?
Tom: I wanted to show you the cabin. We only had another half-hour to go.
Jenny: Well, now we're stuck. What can we do?
Tom: I don't know.
Jenny: I've heard that when this happens, it's important to save energy.
Tom: What do you mean?
Jenny: We're stranded here, Tom. We may be here a long time. We need to conserve the gas in the car. The car's energy is what will keep us warm.
Tom: I have plenty of gas.
Jenny: Yes, but the gas and the battery both have to stay working. We can't just let the car run and run. If we do, it will die soon. Then we'll freeze.
Tom: So what can we do?
Jenny: Turn the lights off. Then, run the car and the heater only about fifteen minutes every hour. That will conserve the heat as long as possible.
Tom: Alright. That's a good idea.
Jenny: I wish we hadn't come up here. Now we'll probably be here for days.
Tom: Days?
Jenny: Yes, it happens. That is what happens in big snowstorms. People get stranded for days.
Tom: Oh, my God! It's good we have food.
Jenny: Probably we'll survive. But turn the car off for about forty-five minutes. Then we'll turn it on again.
<END CONVERSATION>

Jonathan: How are your English and computer skills?
Liu Lichi: I have passed the CET - 4 and 6. As far as computer is concerned I can use the computer for word processing.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
John: What kind of music do you like listening to?
Emma: I like music that has a fast beat and is lively, like dance music. You know, I go to a disco almost every week. Sometimes it's too loud though. You prefer classical music, don't you?
John: Yes, I do. I find it very relaxing. I often listen to Mozart or Bach in the evening after a hard day at work.
Emma: I must admit that I like several pieces of classical music. It's certainly more sophisticated that modern dance music.
John: Classical music is supposed to be good for you brain. Research suggest that it makes your brain more active. Students who listen to classical music while studying perform better.
Emma: Really? Perhaps I should listen to classical music often. I heard that listening to classical music is helpful in reducing stress.
John: Yes. That's why I listen to it in the evenings. I usually play it as background music while I'm cooking or doing other housework.
Emma: I've got a few classical music CD's. I should follow your lead and increase my brain power.
John: You can find plenty of recordings on the internet too. You can listen to samples and then buy them very cheaply if you like them.
Emma: That's a good idea. You should do the same with some music. You might find something you like. Classical music might make you clever, but dance might make you livelier and happier.
<END CONVERSATION>

Carla: What's the accommodation like in London Ahmed?
Ahmed: Well, it's a bit difficult. There are thousands of overseas students here, you know.
Carla: Would it be better to stay in a hotel, to share a flat, or to stay with a family?
Ahmed: It would probably be better to stay with a family to begin with, Carla.
Carla: You wouldn't recommend sharing a flat?
Ahmed: No, I wouldn't move into a flat if I were you. You won't get much studying done in a flat. You'll spend half your time cooking and cleaning.
Carla: How can I find out about families who take in students?
Ahmed: There's a list at the student union building on campus. The people at the student union should be able to help you find a family to stay with.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
Alice: I'm tired of watching television. Let's go to the cinema tonight.
Bob: All right. Do you want to go downtown? Or is there a good movie in the neighborhood?
Alice: I'd rather not spend a lot of money. What does the paper say about neighborhood theaters?
Bob: Here's the list on page... Column 6. Here it is. Where's the Rialto? There's a perfect movie there.
Alice: That's too far away. And it's hard to find a place to park there.
Bob: Well, the Grand Theater has Gone with the Wind.
Alice: I saw that years ago. I couldn't wait to see it again. Moreover, it's too long. We wouldn't get home until midnight.
Bob: The Center has a horror film. You wouldn't want to see that?
Alice: No, indeed. I wouldn't be able to sleep tonight.
Bob: That's about all there is. Unless we change our decision and go downtown.
Alice: No, we just can't pay for it. There must be something else we haven't seen.
Bob: Here, look for yourself, I can't find anything else.
Alice: Look at this!
Bob: What?
Alice: In the television timetable, there's a baseball game on television tonight.
Bob: I wasn't looking for a TV program. I was looking at the movie ads.
Alice: I know, but I just happened to notice it. New York is playing Boston.
Bob: That must be good. I wouldn't mind watching that.
<END CONVERSATION>

Alice: That's not bad, it could be a short-term alternative. Your mom can look for another job when the market improves. Things will workout eventually.
John: I just hope she won't feel depressed.
Alice: How about searching for information on jobs on the internet?
John: That's a good idea, thank you.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
Alice: I watched a very interesting documentary about plants yesterday evening. It was called 'unusual plants' and looked at several species of plants from around the world which have unusual features.
Bob: Really? Tell me about some of the plants they showed.
Alice: Well. There was one type of plant that catches insects and eats them.
Bob: Is that type of plant found in this country?
Alice: No, it isn't. it's a pity, because I'd like to see it in action.
Bob: So would I. what other unusual plants did they show?
Alice: They showed flowers that only provide their nectar to one type of butterfly or bee. The insect has to be the exact size to get the nectar. Other insects cannot get it. Of course, when the insect collects the nectar, it also takes some pollen from one flower to another.
Bob: That's very specialized. So, the insects and the flowers rely on each other. If one became extinct, the other would too.
Alice: That's right. That's one reason why it's so important to protect every species.
Bob: I see. The plants that fascinate me most are cacti. I find it amazing that they can survive in such dry desert conditions.
Alice: According to the documentary, they have an incredible ability to find water supplies, however small, and then store them without losing much through evaporation.
Bob: That's why they often have long roots to find water spines instead of leaves, to reduce water loss.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
John: How is everything going with your girlfriend?
Alex: Didn't I tell you? It's over!
John: Oh, I am sorry to hear that. I didn't know that you had split up. What happened?
Alex: It was a few things. The first thing that happened was that we were supposed to go out for a romantic dinner for our one year anniversary, but she stood me up!
John: Really! Did she tell you why she didn't show up?
Alex: No, but I ended up finding out later that night when I saw her with another man at a club near my home!
John: What was she thinking? Did you confront her about it when you saw her?
Alex: I wanted to, but I knew that if I spoke to her, I'd just blow up at her, so I decided to just go home. I called her later that night, but she didn't answer the phone.
John: I can't believe she would do that to you. It's so dishonest—and rude!
Alex: I know. I still haven't heard from her. The good thing is that I'm so angry with her that I don't feel sad about not having her around.
John: I bet you she regrets what she's done. You were such a good catch! She really lost out, didn't she?
Alex: I guess so. It would be nice to know why she did this though.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
Sophia: May, could you bring this note to Professor Li for me today?
May: Sure, no problem. Asking for leave again? You have been absent from class five times this semester.
Sophia: I know. But attending Miss Li's class is just waste of time. No more than one third of her students will go to her class.
May: I agree that Miss Li doesn't teach so well. Most students either sleep or do other things in her class.
Sophia: Yeah, my boyfriend plays the video game every time in class with me. Or I chat with my friends through text messages.
May: Fortunately her class is just an elective course, not as important as compulsory courses.
Sophia: Right, so we must spare some time to attend selective courses.
May: But isn't it too impolite to be absent?
Sophia: What can I do? I have things to do in Students' Government.
May: Oh, I thought you just gave an excuse on this note.
Sophia: Sometimes I will try various excuses. But this is my last time asking for leave. Or I will have a bad record.
May: Yeah, besides, your credit will be deducted. That is kind of serious.
Sophia: I have been absented from many classes this semester just because of my work in the Students' Government.
May: You can't write with one hand and draw with the other.
Sophia: I am thinking about quitting my job in the student government. But before that, I must do my job. Bye. Don't forget about that note.
May: You can count on me.
<END CONVERSATION>

dialog:
<BEGIN CONVERSATION>
Amy: Have you been ever been to Disneyworld?
John: When I was young, my parents took me to the one in California. I always forget which, is that one Disneyland or Disneyworld?
Amy: The one in Florida is Disneyworld and the one in California is Disneyland, so you must have been to Disneyland.
John: That's right. Why do you ask?
Amy: Well, I've never been to either so I was thinking of going to Disneyworld for my honeymoon.
John: When are getting married?
Amy: Some time next year. We haven't set the date yet.
John: Congratulations! I had no idea.
Amy: Thank you. So what do you think? Would we have a good time?
John: Do you like amusement parks?
Amy: For the most part, yes. Some of the rides are bit too scary for me, though.
John: If you don't think twice about the rides and go on every ride that you can, you'll have a good time.
Amy: Even the roller coasters that go through tunnels in the dark?
John: Even those. It'll be very romantic, I think. You'll have loads of fun.
Amy: Thanks for the advice. I'll talk to my fiance about it tonight.
John: I'm sure he'll love the idea. Just throw yourself into it and you'll enjoy it!
<END CONVERSATION>
